<p>Well&#8230; no. Granted, it redacts the decription, but given the mission-statement of the Foundation, the description is non-essential information. It leaves the actual information on &quot;how to contain or secure [the object]&quot; untouched (save for a few black boxes, but that's something that the people to whom this applies will already know).</p>
<p>The thing is, personnel don't actually <em>need to know</em> what an object is in order to do to it what the Foundation does to these things, i.e., keep it away from the world and make sure it doesn't kill anything. While the major redaction would make this, as a document, essentially useless for research, research is only really allowed to be preformed to learn more about an object, which is only any-kind-of-priority because it helps in its containment - not a problem, though, because in this specific instance, the Foundation finds the risks of research to outweigh any possible benefits.</p>

